üìò Lecture: Big-Omega (Œ©) Notation
(Analysis of Algorithms ‚Äì Teacher‚Äôs Way)
====================================================================

This lecture is about BIG-OMEGA (Œ©).

‚ö†Ô∏è This is NOT a shortcut lecture.
‚ö†Ô∏è This is NOT about memorizing formulas.
‚ö†Ô∏è This is NOT about jumping to answers.

This lecture builds:
- Intuition
- Graphical understanding
- Formal definition
- Constant & n‚ÇÄ logic
- Proofs
- Failed cases
- Final conclusions

--------------------------------------------------------------------
1. Background Before Definition (Very Important)
--------------------------------------------------------------------
Before reading the definition of Big-Omega, the teacher first builds
the BACKGROUND.

In the previous lectures:
- Big-O was completed properly
- We understood growth of functions
- We used graphs to understand comparisons

Now we do the SAME thing for Big-Omega.

Do NOT rush to the definition.
First understand WHAT Big-Omega is trying to say.

--------------------------------------------------------------------
2. What Are We Comparing?
--------------------------------------------------------------------
We always compare TWO functions:

- f(n) ‚Üí running time of algorithm
- g(n) ‚Üí reference function

x-axis  ‚Üí input size (n)
y-axis  ‚Üí running time

We DO NOT care about:
- small inputs
- behavior before n‚ÇÄ

We ONLY care about:
üëâ behavior AFTER n‚ÇÄ

This idea is EXTREMELY important.

--------------------------------------------------------------------
3. Graphical Understanding (Free Style Explanation)
--------------------------------------------------------------------
Consider a function f(n).

This function:
- goes up
- goes down
- fluctuates
- behaves randomly

But after a certain point n‚ÇÄ:
üëâ its behavior becomes predictable.

In Big-Omega:
We want to make sure that AFTER n‚ÇÄ:

f(n) is ALWAYS
GREATER THAN OR EQUAL TO
c ¬∑ g(n)

Before n‚ÇÄ:
- f(n) can be anything
- c¬∑g(n) can be anything
- we DO NOT CARE

Teacher repeatedly says:
üëâ ‚ÄúBefore n‚ÇÄ, my eyes are closed.‚Äù

--------------------------------------------------------------------
4. Core Intuition of Big-Omega
--------------------------------------------------------------------
Big-Omega talks about a **LOWER BOUND**.

Meaning:
- The algorithm will NOT run faster than this
- It will take AT LEAST this much time

So Big-Omega answers:
üëâ ‚ÄúWhat is the minimum guaranteed growth?‚Äù

--------------------------------------------------------------------
5. Symbolic Meaning
--------------------------------------------------------------------
Big-Omega uses:

‚â•   (greater than or equal to)

Big-O used:
‚â§   (less than or equal to)

This is the KEY difference.

--------------------------------------------------------------------
6. Formal Definition of Big-Omega (Œ©)
--------------------------------------------------------------------
Given two functions f(n) and g(n):

We say:

f(n) = Œ©(g(n))

IF AND ONLY IF:

There exists:
- a positive constant c
- a value n‚ÇÄ

Such that:

f(n) ‚â• c ¬∑ g(n)    for all n ‚â• n‚ÇÄ

--------------------------------------------------------------------
7. Meaning of Each Term (Very Important)
--------------------------------------------------------------------
- c ‚Üí positive constant (can be small or large)
- n‚ÇÄ ‚Üí threshold point
- for all n ‚â• n‚ÇÄ ‚Üí forever after that point

If EVEN ONE value after n‚ÇÄ violates the inequality:
üëâ Big-Omega relation FAILS.

--------------------------------------------------------------------
8. Graphical Visualization
--------------------------------------------------------------------
On the graph:

- f(n) curve is ABOVE c¬∑g(n)
- After n‚ÇÄ, they NEVER cross
- Touching is allowed
- Crossing is NOT allowed

If f(n) goes below c¬∑g(n) after n‚ÇÄ:
‚ùå Not Big-Omega

--------------------------------------------------------------------
9. Question 1
--------------------------------------------------------------------
Given:
f(n) = 3n + 2
g(n) = n

Check:
f(n) = Œ©(g(n)) ?

--------------------------------------------------------------------
10. Proof Logic (Teacher Flow)
--------------------------------------------------------------------
We must prove:

3n + 2 ‚â• c ¬∑ n   for all n ‚â• n‚ÇÄ

Choose:
c = 1

Then inequality becomes:
3n + 2 ‚â• n

This is TRUE for:
n ‚â• 1

So:
c = 1
n‚ÇÄ = 1

Hence:
f(n) = Œ©(n)

--------------------------------------------------------------------
11. Reverse Check (Very Important)
--------------------------------------------------------------------
Now check:
g(n) = Œ©(f(n)) ?

That means:
n ‚â• c(3n + 2)

This is NOT possible for all n ‚â• n‚ÇÄ.

No matter what constant c you choose:
3n + 2 grows faster than n.

Hence:
g(n) ‚â† Œ©(f(n))

--------------------------------------------------------------------
12. Question 2
--------------------------------------------------------------------
Given:
f(n) = 5n¬≤ + 6n + 2
g(n) = n¬≤

Check:
f(n) = Œ©(g(n)) ?

--------------------------------------------------------------------
13. Direct Observation
--------------------------------------------------------------------
Dominating term of f(n) is n¬≤.

So intuitively:
f(n) SHOULD be Œ©(n¬≤).

Now prove it formally.

--------------------------------------------------------------------
14. Formal Proof
--------------------------------------------------------------------
We want:
5n¬≤ + 6n + 2 ‚â• c ¬∑ n¬≤

Choose:
c = 1

Then:
5n¬≤ + 6n + 2 ‚â• n¬≤

This holds for:
n ‚â• 1

So:
c = 1
n‚ÇÄ = 1

Hence:
f(n) = Œ©(n¬≤)

--------------------------------------------------------------------
15. Reverse Direction
--------------------------------------------------------------------
Check:
n¬≤ = Œ©(5n¬≤ + 6n + 2) ?

Try constants.

No matter how large n becomes:
n¬≤ cannot dominate 5n¬≤ + 6n + 2.

So:
n¬≤ ‚â† Œ©(f(n))

--------------------------------------------------------------------
16. Question 3 (Failure Case)
--------------------------------------------------------------------
Given:
f(n) = 1000n
g(n) = n¬≤

Check:
f(n) = Œ©(g(n)) ?

We need:
1000n ‚â• c ¬∑ n¬≤

Rearrange:
1000 ‚â• c ¬∑ n

This CANNOT hold for all n ‚â• n‚ÇÄ.

As n increases, RHS grows infinitely.

So:
‚ùå f(n) ‚â† Œ©(n¬≤)

--------------------------------------------------------------------
17. Reverse Case
--------------------------------------------------------------------
Check:
n¬≤ = Œ©(1000n)

Try:
n¬≤ ‚â• c ¬∑ 1000n

Choose:
c = 1

Then:
n¬≤ ‚â• 1000n
n ‚â• 1000

So:
c = 1
n‚ÇÄ = 1000

Hence:
n¬≤ = Œ©(1000n)

--------------------------------------------------------------------
18. Constant Time Case
--------------------------------------------------------------------
Question:
If time taken by algorithm is independent of input size,
what is its Big-Omega?

Let:
f(n) = 1000

We want:
1000 ‚â• c ¬∑ 1

Choose:
c = 1
n‚ÇÄ = 1

Hence:
f(n) = Œ©(1)

So:
Any constant time algorithm is Œ©(1).

--------------------------------------------------------------------
19. Important Insight
--------------------------------------------------------------------
Œ©(1) does NOT mean time = 1.

It means:
Time is AT LEAST constant.

1000, 5000, 10 ‚Üí all are Œ©(1).

--------------------------------------------------------------------
20. Dominating Term Rule (Teacher Rule)
--------------------------------------------------------------------
For Big-Omega:
üëâ Always take the DOMINATING TERM.

Example:
5n¬≤ + 6n + 2 ‚Üí Œ©(n¬≤)

Lower terms do NOT matter.

--------------------------------------------------------------------
21. Very Important Concept
--------------------------------------------------------------------
Œ© does NOT represent a single function.

Œ© represents a SET of functions.

Example:
If f(n) = 5n¬≤ + 6n + 2

Then f(n) is:
Œ©(n¬≤)
Œ©(n)
Œ©(log n)
Œ©(1)

All smaller or equal growth functions are valid.

--------------------------------------------------------------------
22. Comparison with Big-O (Conceptual Only)
--------------------------------------------------------------------
- Big-O ‚Üí Upper Bound
- Big-Omega ‚Üí Lower Bound

Big-Omega guarantees:
‚ÄúThe algorithm will NOT be faster than this.‚Äù

--------------------------------------------------------------------
23. Stock Market Analogy (Teacher Analogy)
--------------------------------------------------------------------
Think of a graph fluctuating.

- Upper boundary ‚Üí Big-O
- Lower boundary ‚Üí Big-Omega

The function may move up and down,
but it NEVER crosses the lower bound.

--------------------------------------------------------------------
24. Final Conclusions
--------------------------------------------------------------------
- Big-Omega gives a LOWER bound
- Constants do not matter
- Dominating term matters
- Before n‚ÇÄ behavior is irrelevant
- Œ© represents infinite functions
- It guarantees minimum growth

--------------------------------------------------------------------
25. One-Line Definition
--------------------------------------------------------------------
Big-Omega (Œ©) represents the set of functions
that grow AT LEAST as fast as a given function
for sufficiently large input size.

